commended as an addition for muscle recovery and bone density. Current magnesium oxide supplement has low bioavailability. --- Current state Michelle has been navigating a recovery period from a short-term wellness situation requiring a treatment course. Training was modified accordingly: full rest when actively unwell, then scaled sessions (two sets, glute/posterior chain focus, substituting glute bridges for KB swings to avoid respiratory strain) as energy returned. The distinction between "low motivation days" (minimum effort rule applies) and "actively unwell days" (full rest appropriate) has been established as a coaching principle. The fitness PWA is live and actively used. Recent programme update to Day C added the Banded Cossack Squat (bodyweight + light band, 45° max depth, 8 each side) as the first post-warmup exercise, replaced Single-Leg Hip Thrust with Banded Single-Leg Glute Bridge (band above knees, push outward, left-side hip-level cue), and removed the sissy squat (high compressive load counterproductive to knee goals). --- On the horizon Queued PWA updates: Stationary bike logging redesigned for duration, average heart rate, and RPE (Zone 2 reference range: 101–118 bpm displayed) Plank hold changed to bodyweight and seconds Bird dog changed to bodyweight and seconds De-Googling the PWA is a low-priority project with a phased plan: Google Fonts first → Google Auth to Proton Pass → Calendar API last (pending Proton Calendar API maturity). A reminder has been set for December 2026 to revisit this. A companion protein/nutrition tracker app is also in the pipeline. --- Key learnings & principles The knee problem is a hip stability problem: the left knee is absorbing load due to hip instability, requiring neuromuscular re-education. Band cues during squats are the mechanism, not a regression. Michelle self-discovered that banded goblet, sissy, and regular squats felt significantly better — independent validation of the hip stability hypothesis. On unwell